{"title_page": "Parker Pen Company", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2012}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Parker Pen Company\n| logo = Parker Pen Company logo.svg\n| caption = \n| type = [[Subsidiary]]\n| genre = \n| fate = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| foundation = {{start date and age|1888}}\n| founder = [[George Safford Parker]]\n| defunct = \n| location_city = [[Newhaven, East Sussex]]\n| location_country = [[UK]] (until 2011)\n| location = [[Nantes]] France (after 2011)\n| locations = \n| area_served = Worldwide[India]\n| key_people = George Safford Parker, <small>founder</small>, <br/>Kenneth Parker <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.internet-ink.com/blog/Pens/2016/04/12-Parker-Pen-History|title=Parker Pen History - Pens - Internet Ink|website=Internet Ink|accessdate=26 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180426020807/https://www.internet-ink.com/blog/Pens/2016/04/12-Parker-Pen-History|archivedate=26 April 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| industry = [[Writing instrument]]s\n| products = [[Fountain pen]]s, [[ballpoint pen]]s\n| services = \n| revenue = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| aum = \n| assets = \n| equity = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = \n| parent = [[Newell Brands]]\n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| homepage = [http://www.parkerpen.com www.parkerpen.com]\n| footnotes = \n| intl = \n}}\nThe '''Parker Pen Company''' is an [[United States of America|American]] manufacturer of luxury pens, founded in 1888<ref name=timeline>{{cite web|url=http://www.parkerpen.com/en/discovery/making_of/timeline|title=Sorry|website=www.parkerpen.com|accessdate=26 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130902045402/http://www.parkerpen.com/en/discovery/making_of/timeline|archivedate=2 September 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> by [[George Safford Parker]] in [[Janesville, Wisconsin]], United States.  In 2011 the Parker factory at [[Newhaven, East Sussex]], England, was closed, and its production transferred to [[Nantes]], France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/sussex/8154432.stm|title=Pen factory closure plan revealed|author=|date=16 July 2009|publisher=|accessdate=26 April 2018|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Gold Parker I.M Pen.JPG|thumb|200px|left|A gold Parker I.M. pen]]\n\n[[George Safford Parker]], the founder, had previously been a sales agent for the [[John Holland Gold Pen Company]]. He received his first [[fountain pen]] related [[patent]] in 1889.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://patents.google.com/patent/US416944A/en|title=George safford parker|website=google.com|accessdate=26 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180426020807/https://patents.google.com/patent/US416944A/en|archivedate=26 April 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  In 1894 Parker received a patent on his \"Lucky Curve\" fountain pen feed,<ref>[http://www.google.com/patents/US512319 US patent n.512319] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140611113959/http://www.google.com/patents/US512319 |date=11 June 2014 }}.</ref> which was claimed to draw excess ink back into the pen barrel when the pen was not in use.  The company's first successful pen, released in 1899, was the [[Parker Jointless]]. The Lucky Curve feed was used in various forms until 1928.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fountainpen.it/The_Parker_Pen_Company/en|title=Parker/en - FountainPen|website=www.fountainpen.it|accessdate=26 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180426020807/http://www.fountainpen.it/The_Parker_Pen_Company/en|archivedate=26 April 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Parker Frontier Ball-point Pen.jpg|thumb|200px|left|a Parker Frontier Ball-point Pen]]\nFrom the 1920s to the 1960s, before the development of the [[ballpoint pen]], Parker was either number one or number two in worldwide writing instrument sales. In 1931 Parker created [[Quink]] (quick drying ink), which eliminated the need for blotting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parkerpen.com/en/discovery/inks/quink|title=Sorry|website=www.parkerpen.com|accessdate=26 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130527131803/http://www.parkerpen.com/en/discovery/inks/quink|archivedate=27 May 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 1941 the company developed the most widely used model of fountain pen in history (over $400 million worth of sales in its 30-year history), the [[Parker 51]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://parkerpens.net/parker51.html|title=Parker Penography: PARKER 51|website=parkerpens.net|accessdate=26 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022154247/http://www.parkerpens.net/parker51.html|archivedate=22 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.booksaboutpens.com/catalog_en/index.asp?id=2763|title=Books About Pens|website=www.booksaboutpens.com|accessdate=26 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708082949/http://www.booksaboutpens.com/catalog_en/index.asp?id=2763|archivedate=8 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Manufacturing facilities were set up over the years in Canada, United Kingdom, Denmark, France, Mexico, USA, Pakistan, India, Germany (Osmia-Parker), Brazil and Argentina.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\n[[File:Duofold Desk Set.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Parker [[Duofold]] desk set, 1930]]\n\nIn 1955, the company introduced its Liquid Lead pencil which used liquid graphite to write like a pen.  Unfortunately, the [[Scripto]] company had introduced a similar product called Fluidlead a few months previously.  To avoid a costly patent fight the companies agreed to share their formulas with each other.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://parkerpens.net/liquidlead.html | title=Vintage Pen Blog | publisher=GoPens.com | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170906034612/https://parkerpens.net/liquidlead.html | archivedate=6 September 2017 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe company bought retailer and catalog company [[Norm Thompson (company)|Norm Thompson]] in 1973, and then sold it in 1981.<ref>{{cite news | title=Portland\u2019s Norm Thompson is 40 and still growing| last=Hambug| first=Ken  |date=20 November 1989|work=The Oregonian| page=C9}}</ref> In 1976 Parker acquired [[Manpower Inc.|Manpower]] just as the temporary staffing market was surging.  In time Manpower provided more revenue than the pen business.  A 1982 spinoff, Sintered Specialties, Inc., became SSI Technologies, a manufacturer of automotive sensors.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\nA management buyout in 1986 moved the company's headquarters to [[Newhaven, East Sussex]], England, which was the original location of the Valentine Pen Company previously acquired by Parker. In 1993 Parker was purchased by the [[Gillette Company]], which already owned the [[Paper Mate]] brand - the best-selling disposable ballpoint. In 2000 Gillette sold its writing instruments division to the company [[Newell Rubbermaid]], whose Sanford Stationery Division became the largest writing instrument manufacturers in the world at that time, simultaneously owning such brand names as [[Rotring]], Sharpie, Reynolds as well as Parker, PaperMate, [[Waterman pens|Waterman]], and [[Liquid Paper]].{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\nWith commercial competition increasing upon the Parker jotter's classic metal ink refill cartridge design from low cost generic copies produced in [[China]], as Parker's unique design [[patent]] for the cartridge expired, Parker's sales began to be drastically adversely affected. In July 2009 ''Newell Rubbermaid Inc.'' in response announced that it had decided to close down the Parker production factory at Newhaven in England with the dismissal of 180 employees from the facility, and relocate production to France.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/sussex/8154432.stm Sussex Edition] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090726142930/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/sussex/8154432.stm |date=26 July 2009 }}; [[BBC News]].</ref> The following month, Newell Rubbermaid Inc. announced that the factory in [[Janesville, Wisconsin]], was also to close the remaining operation there producing Parker Pens (which eliminated a further 153 manufacturing jobs).  The company press release stated: \"This decision is a response to structural issues accelerated by market trends and is in no way a reflection on the highly valued work performed by our Janesville employees over the years.\" Newell Rubbermaid offered 'transitional employment services' along with severance pay in compensation to the dismissed workforce.<ref>[http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/4497779.Parker_Pen_Newhaven_closure_plan_revealed/ Parker Pen Newhaven closure plan revealed] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610193630/http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/4497779.Parker_Pen_Newhaven_closure_plan_revealed/ |date=10 June 2015 }}, The Argus, 16 July 2009</ref><ref>[http://host.madison.com/news/local/article_51d86c10-921d-5dc0-bbd8-9479f584fd01.html Sanford leaving Janesville] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120823233657/http://host.madison.com/news/local/article_51d86c10-921d-5dc0-bbd8-9479f584fd01.html |date=23 August 2012 }}, Madison.com, 19 August 2009</ref>\n\nSubsequently, Parker has abandoned its traditional retail outlets in North America. While some of its former staple Jotter pens may be found in retailers such as [[Office Depot]], the Parker line has been moved to upscale \"luxury\" retailers in an abandonment of its former business model of quality manufacture combined with mass market appeal and pricing.{{Citation needed|date=November 2011}} With this commercial strategic move Parker also altered its traditional product warranty on its high end pens, changing the former lifetime guarantee to a two-year warranty limitation.<ref>[http://www.parkerpen.com/en-US/warranty Parker Official Website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140309120736/http://www.parkerpen.com/en-US/warranty |date=9 March 2014 }}</ref>\n\nParker Pen Company holds two [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Royal Warrant of Appointment (United Kingdom)|royal warrant]]s, one from [[Queen Elizabeth II]] (since 1962) and one from the [[Prince Charles|Prince of Wales]] (since 1990).<ref>{{cite web |title=PARKER CELEBRATES THE BRITISH MONARCH |url=https://www.parkerpen.com/en-GB/parker-celebrates-Queen-Elizabeths-90th-year |website=parkerpen.com |accessdate=12 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nParker Pen Co. was an aviation  pioneer. The interest of Parker Pen Co. about aircraft came from Kenneth Parker, son of the founder, he enlisted in the fledgling air service and, after flight training at Miami Air Base, Kenneth was assigned to officer training in tactical maneuvers at Pensacola Naval Air Station, Florida. From their first company business plane, the Parker Duofold Fairchild, they used it as an innovative advertising weapon inviting his dealers.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Campos |first1=Ramon |title=Parker: An invitation to fly. | url=https://estilograficas.mforos.com/1176620/13017601-parker-una-invitacion-a-volar-el-libro/}}</ref>\n\n==US Presidential Parkers==\nParker Jotters were a favorite choice of President [[John F. Kennedy]] for signing legislation and to give as gifts.<ref>{{cite web|title=John F. Kennedy Parker Jotter Pen|url=http://store.jfklibrary.org/john-f-kennedy-parker-jotter-pen/paaaiacnmfeikfdc/product|website=John F. Kennedy Presidential Library and Museum|publisher=JFK Library and museum|accessdate=3 February 2017|quote=President Kennedy's Favorite Pen|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905183343/http://store.jfklibrary.org/john-f-kennedy-parker-jotter-pen/paaaiacnmfeikfdc/product|archivedate=5 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Indeed, successive presidents from Kennedy to Clinton used Parker pens for these purposes, and Parker retained a special representative, John W. Gibbs, to handle White House orders. In one of his early years in office, [[Lyndon Johnson]] ordered no less than 60,000 Parker pens. LBJ would use up to 75 pens to sign each important document and bill, writing different strokes of the letters of his name with different pens, and giving them all away to allies and supporters with little typed certificates. After Parker ceased to be an American-owned company, later presidents switched to using [[A. T. Cross Company]] pens.<ref name=\"Loring\">{{cite web|last1=Loring|first1=John|title=The Presidential Pen - the first fifty years|url=http://www.loringpage.com/attpensetc/penbookupdate.html|publisher=John Loring|accessdate=3 February 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161227012404/http://www.loringpage.com/attpensetc/penbookupdate.html|archivedate=27 December 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bill Clinton Parker Insignia Set.jpg|thumb|Bill Clinton Parker Insignia Set]]\n\n==Famous models==\n[[File:Sonnet parker 3n06.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Sonnet, made from 1993]]\n\nKey models in the company's history include:\n<div style=\"-moz-column-count:3; column-count:3;\">\n* [[Parker Jointless|Jointless]] (1899), \n* Jack Knife Safety (1909), \n* [[Duofold (pen)|Duofold]] (1921), \n* [[Parker Vacumatic|Vacumatic]] (1932), \n* [[Parker 51|\"51\"]] (1941), \n* The [[Jotter]] (1954), \n* 61 (1956), \n* 45 (1964),\n* 75 (1964), \n* Classic (1967), \n* 25 (1975), \n* Arrow (1982), \n* Vector (1986), \n* Duofold International (1987),\n* 95 (1988), \n* Sonnet (1993), and \n* Parker 100 (2004)\n</div>\n{{clear}}\n\n[[Image:Parker-Vector-Plastic.jpg|thumb|eft|150px|Parker Vector plastic type]]\n[[Image:Parker-Vector-Steel.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Parker Vector steel [[Rollerball pen|rollerball tip]] type]]\n[[File:Parker Fountain pen.jpg|thumb|150px|Vector steel [[fountain pen]] type]]\n\n\n\n=== Parker 25 === \n\n[[File:Parker 25 flighters.jpg|thumb|Parker 25 flighters]]\n\nThe Parker 25 was a pen introduced by the [[Parker Pen Company]] in 1975. Created by the renowned designer [[Kenneth Grange]] based on a detailed brief,<ref> See Malcolm Toak, ''Pen to Paper, The Story of Newhaven's Pen Factory'', New Anzac Publications, 2005</ref> it was manufactured in [[Newhaven]], England and produced in a variety of different versions until 1999.<ref>See Parker Pens website, by Swedish pen historian Tony Fischier http://parkerpens.net/parker25.html</ref> An eye-catching, contemporary-looking pen, with mainly steel components, the Parker 25 was intended to revive the company's fortunes. As ''The Guardian'' wrote, '(Grange's) classic Parker pen had the machined lustre of a bullet. In fact, its tapering barrel was inspired by an American space rocket, a form that enabled the lid to be the same diameter as the pen no matter which end it was attached to.'<ref>Justin McQuirk, 'Kenneth Grange, a very British modernist', ''The Guardian'', 19 July 2011, https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2011/jul/19/kenneth-grange-british-modernist</ref> It was affordable enough to become a staple entry-level pen for both work and leisure uses - and for secondary school students at a time when fountain pens were still obligatory in many British schools. Advertising slogans used to market Parker 25s included 'Modern as Tomorrow', 'Space Age Design, Space Age Performance', 'European Styled' and 'Contemporary, Highly Functional Design'.<ref>See examples at More Engineering website created by former Parker engineer, http://www.moreengineering.co.uk/publications-and-prices/4584108238</ref>\n\nParker 25s were issued in several variants: initially, fountain pen, ballpoint, fibre point and mechanical pencil.<ref>http://www.moreengineering.co.uk/models/458277434</ref> A rollerball model was introduced in 1981, and fibre tips were phased out a couple of years later. While the great majority of Parker 25s were 'flighters', with a brushed steel finish, matte black and later white versions were issued between 1978 and 1987. The pens had four different trim colours - blue (the most common), black, green, and most rarely of all, orange. Orange trim Parker 25s were discontinued in 1976 following a copyright dispute with [[Rotring]], and surviving examples are very sought after. A striking feature of all Parker 25s is the square plastic tassie logo on the clip.\n\nThe earliest Mark I Parker 25 fountain pens dating from the first year of production feature a distinctive breather hole in the nib. While the original models had a flat plastic circle on top of the cap, Mark III and IV pens have a round ridge on this inner cap. Pens manufactured from 1980 feature letter date codes which were changed every quarter. Those manufactured from 1990 are stamped 'Made in UK'; earlier pens were inscribed 'Made in England'. Pens without any manufacture stamps, or inscribed 'Made in Aust', are very rare. Parker 25s were all assembled in Britain by hand<ref>http://www.moreengineering.co.uk/introduction/4582901246</ref> - unlike Jotters, Vectors and other mass market pens - and were very minimalist, comprising between 9 and 11 components.\n\nThe 25 was an extremely successful pen for Parker commercially, especially during its first decade or so of production.<ref>https://parkerpens.net/parker25.html</ref> A number of promotional versions were made up to order, featuring company logos on the barrel (the matte black and white versions were often branded in this way), clip or cap.\n\nSome pen aficionados are rather disparaging about the Parker 25, which lacks the status of the legendary [[Parker Duofold]]<ref>See David Shepherd and Dan Zazove, ''Parker Duofold'', Surrenden Pens Ltd, 2006.</ref> or the storied [[Parker 51]]. <ref>See David Shepherd and Mark Shepherd, ''Parker \"51\"'', Surrenden Pens Ltd, 2004.</ref> But in recent years they have been enjoying a revival, their space age look evoking nostalgia for the final quarter of the twentieth century. The Parker 25 was even given the accolade of an exhibition stand at the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]].<ref>Kenneth Grange at the Boilerhouse, Parker 25, ''Design Council Slide Collection'', Victoria and Albert Museum, https://vads.ac.uk/large.php?uid=53760&sos=0</ref>.\n\n\n===Parker Vector===\nThe precursor to the Parker Vector was introduced in 1981.  It was a simple cylindrical plastic cap and barrel [[roller-ball pen]] called the \"Parker RB1\".<ref>Note: The RB1 name stands for \"Rollerball 1\".</ref>  In 1984, Parker added the FP1 (\"Fountain Pen 1\"), with essentially the same design.  The RB1 and FP1 models were produced until 1986, at which time Parker revised the pen by lengthening the cap and shortening the barrel and renaming the new pen the \"Vector Standard\".  Presently, there are four models available (in plastic and steel): the fountain pen, capped rollerball, pushbutton ballpoint, and pushbutton pencil.<ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703493504576007640835661876 ''When Parker Pens Ruled''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170812073307/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703493504576007640835661876 |date=12 August 2017 }}; Tuesday, December 7, 2010; article; [[The Wall Street Journal]]; comment: about the relaunch of Parker Pens held at the Museum of Arts and Design on Columbus Circle.  Pictured are two Parker Vectors with polished steel finish; retrieved ???.</ref>\n\n==Products==\n*'''Products offered by the Parker Pen Company {{Asof|2012|lc=y}}:'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parkerpen.com/#/en/press|title=Welcome to Parker|website=www.parkerpen.com|accessdate=26 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315102238/http://www.parkerpen.com/#/en/press|archivedate=15 March 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left\"\n! Type !! Model\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[Parker 5TH|5TH Technology]] || I.M., Ingenuity, Sonnet, Urban\n|-\n|align=center| [[Fountain pen]]s || [[Parker Duofold|Duofold]], Premier, Frontier, Sonnet, Facet, Esprit, Urban, I.M., Vector, [[Parker Jotter|Jotter]]\n|-\n|align=center| [[Ballpoint pen]]s || Reflex, Facet, Executive, Esprit, Frontier, Urban, I.M., Vector, Jotter\n|-\n|align=center| [[Ink]]s and refills || [[Quink]], 5TH Mode\n|}\n</center>\n\n==See also==\n=== Parker brands and models ===\n* [[Parker Jointless|Jointless]]\n* [[Parker Duofold|Duofold]]\n* [[Parker 100|100]]\n* [[Parker 51|51]]\n* [[Jotter]]\n* [[Parker Vacumatic|Vacumatic]]\n* [[Parker Vector|Vector]]\n* [[Quink]]\n* [[List of pen types, brands and companies]]\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{Reflist|25em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Parker|Parker Pens}}\n* [http://www.parkerpen.com Official site]\n* [http://www.parkercollector.com Information site for 130 years of Parker pens]\n* [http://www.penhero.com/PenGallery/Parker/Parker.htm Parker pens gallery on Penhero site]\n \n{{Pen manufacturers}}\n{{Fountain pen manufacturers}}\n{{Manpower Inc.}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:British Royal Warrant holders]]\n[[Category:Fountain pen and ink manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies established in 1888]]\n[[Category:Newell Brands]]\n[[Category:Parker pens| ]]\n[[Category:Pen manufacturers]]\n[[Category:1993 mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:2000 mergers and acquisitions]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2012}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Parker Pen Company\n| logo = Parker Pen Company logo.svg\n| caption = \n| type = [[Subsidiary]]\n| genre = \n| fate = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| foundation = {{start date and age|1888}}\n| founder = [[George Safford Parker]]\n| defunct = \n| location_city = [[Newhaven, East Sussex]]\n| location_country = [[UK]] (until 2011)\n| location = [[Nantes]] France (after 2011)\n| locations = \n| area_served = Worldwide[India]\n| key_people = George Safford Parker, <small>founder</small>, <br/>Kenneth Parker <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.internet-ink.com/blog/Pens/2016/04/12-Parker-Pen-History|title=Parker Pen History - Pens - Internet Ink|website=Internet Ink|accessdate=26 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180426020807/https://www.internet-ink.com/blog/Pens/2016/04/12-Parker-Pen-History|archivedate=26 April 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| industry = [[Writing instrument]]s\n| products = [[Fountain pen]]s, [[ballpoint pen]]s\n| services = \n| revenue = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| aum = \n| assets = \n| equity = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = \n| parent = [[Newell Brands]]\n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| homepage = [http://www.parkerpen.com www.parkerpen.com]\n| footnotes = \n| intl = \n}}\nThe '''Parker Pen Company''' is an [[United States of America|American]] manufacturer of luxury pens, founded in 1888<ref name=timeline>{{cite web|url=http://www.parkerpen.com/en/discovery/making_of/timeline|title=Sorry|website=www.parkerpen.com|accessdate=26 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130902045402/http://www.parkerpen.com/en/discovery/making_of/timeline|archivedate=2 September 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> by [[George Safford Parker]] in [[Janesville, Wisconsin]], United States.  In 2011 the Parker factory at [[Newhaven, East Sussex]], England, was closed, and its production transferred to [[Nantes]], France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/sussex/8154432.stm|title=Pen factory closure plan revealed|author=|date=16 July 2009|publisher=|accessdate=26 April 2018|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Gold Parker I.M Pen.JPG|thumb|200px|left|A gold Parker I.M. pen]]\n\n[[George Safford Parker]], the founder, had previously been a sales agent for the [[John Holland Gold Pen Company]]. He received his first [[fountain pen]] related [[patent]] in 1889.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://patents.google.com/patent/US416944A/en|title=George safford parker|website=google.com|accessdate=26 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180426020807/https://patents.google.com/patent/US416944A/en|archivedate=26 April 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  In 1894 Parker received a patent on his \"Lucky Curve\" fountain pen feed,<ref>[http://www.google.com/patents/US512319 US patent n.512319] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140611113959/http://www.google.com/patents/US512319 |date=11 June 2014 }}.</ref> which was claimed to draw excess ink back into the pen barrel when the pen was not in use.  The company's first successful pen, released in 1899, was the [[Parker Jointless]]. The Lucky Curve feed was used in various forms until 1928.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fountainpen.it/The_Parker_Pen_Company/en|title=Parker/en - FountainPen|website=www.fountainpen.it|accessdate=26 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180426020807/http://www.fountainpen.it/The_Parker_Pen_Company/en|archivedate=26 April 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Parker Frontier Ball-point Pen.jpg|thumb|200px|left|a Parker Frontier Ball-point Pen]]\nFrom the 1920s to the 1960s, before the development of the [[ballpoint pen]], Parker was either number one or number two in worldwide writing instrument sales. In 1931 Parker created [[Quink]] (quick drying ink), which eliminated the need for blotting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parkerpen.com/en/discovery/inks/quink|title=Sorry|website=www.parkerpen.com|accessdate=26 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130527131803/http://www.parkerpen.com/en/discovery/inks/quink|archivedate=27 May 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 1941 the company developed the most widely used model of fountain pen in history (over $400 million worth of sales in its 30-year history), the [[Parker 51]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://parkerpens.net/parker51.html|title=Parker Penography: PARKER 51|website=parkerpens.net|accessdate=26 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022154247/http://www.parkerpens.net/parker51.html|archivedate=22 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.booksaboutpens.com/catalog_en/index.asp?id=2763|title=Books About Pens|website=www.booksaboutpens.com|accessdate=26 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708082949/http://www.booksaboutpens.com/catalog_en/index.asp?id=2763|archivedate=8 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Manufacturing facilities were set up over the years in Canada, United Kingdom, Denmark, France, Mexico, USA, Pakistan, India, Germany (Osmia-Parker), Brazil and Argentina.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\n[[File:Duofold Desk Set.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Parker [[Duofold]] desk set, 1930]]\n\nIn 1955, the company introduced its Liquid Lead pencil which used liquid graphite to write like a pen.  Unfortunately, the [[Scripto]] company had introduced a similar product called Fluidlead a few months previously.  To avoid a costly patent fight the companies agreed to share their formulas with each other.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://parkerpens.net/liquidlead.html | title=Vintage Pen Blog | publisher=GoPens.com | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170906034612/https://parkerpens.net/liquidlead.html | archivedate=6 September 2017 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe company bought retailer and catalog company [[Norm Thompson (company)|Norm Thompson]] in 1973, and then sold it in 1981.<ref>{{cite news | title=Portland\u2019s Norm Thompson is 40 and still growing| last=Hambug| first=Ken  |date=20 November 1989|work=The Oregonian| page=C9}}</ref> In 1976 Parker acquired [[Manpower Inc.|Manpower]] just as the temporary staffing market was surging.  In time Manpower provided more revenue than the pen business.  A 1982 spinoff, Sintered Specialties, Inc., became SSI Technologies, a manufacturer of automotive sensors.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\nA management buyout in 1986 moved the company's headquarters to [[Newhaven, East Sussex]], England, which was the original location of the Valentine Pen Company previously acquired by Parker. In 1993 Parker was purchased by the [[Gillette Company]], which already owned the [[Paper Mate]] brand - the best-selling disposable ballpoint. In 2000 Gillette sold its writing instruments division to the company [[Newell Rubbermaid]], whose Sanford Stationery Division became the largest writing instrument manufacturers in the world at that time, simultaneously owning such brand names as [[Rotring]], Sharpie, Reynolds as well as Parker, PaperMate, [[Waterman pens|Waterman]], and [[Liquid Paper]].{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\nWith commercial competition increasing upon the Parker jotter's classic metal ink refill cartridge design from low cost generic copies produced in [[China]], as Parker's unique design [[patent]] for the cartridge expired, Parker's sales began to be drastically adversely affected. In July 2009 ''Newell Rubbermaid Inc.'' in response announced that it had decided to close down the Parker production factory at Newhaven in England with the dismissal of 180 employees from the facility, and relocate production to France.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/sussex/8154432.stm Sussex Edition] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090726142930/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/sussex/8154432.stm |date=26 July 2009 }}; [[BBC News]].</ref> The following month, Newell Rubbermaid Inc. announced that the factory in [[Janesville, Wisconsin]], was also to close the remaining operation there producing Parker Pens (which eliminated a further 153 manufacturing jobs).  The company press release stated: \"This decision is a response to structural issues accelerated by market trends and is in no way a reflection on the highly valued work performed by our Janesville employees over the years.\" Newell Rubbermaid offered 'transitional employment services' along with severance pay in compensation to the dismissed workforce.<ref>[http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/4497779.Parker_Pen_Newhaven_closure_plan_revealed/ Parker Pen Newhaven closure plan revealed] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610193630/http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/4497779.Parker_Pen_Newhaven_closure_plan_revealed/ |date=10 June 2015 }}, The Argus, 16 July 2009</ref><ref>[http://host.madison.com/news/local/article_51d86c10-921d-5dc0-bbd8-9479f584fd01.html Sanford leaving Janesville] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120823233657/http://host.madison.com/news/local/article_51d86c10-921d-5dc0-bbd8-9479f584fd01.html |date=23 August 2012 }}, Madison.com, 19 August 2009</ref>\n\nSubsequently, Parker has abandoned its traditional retail outlets in North America. While some of its former staple Jotter pens may be found in retailers such as [[Office Depot]], the Parker line has been moved to upscale \"luxury\" retailers in an abandonment of its former business model of quality manufacture combined with mass market appeal and pricing.{{Citation needed|date=November 2011}} With this commercial strategic move Parker also altered its traditional product warranty on its high end pens, changing the former lifetime guarantee to a two-year warranty limitation.<ref>[http://www.parkerpen.com/en-US/warranty Parker Official Website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140309120736/http://www.parkerpen.com/en-US/warranty |date=9 March 2014 }}</ref>\n\nParker Pen Company holds two [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Royal Warrant of Appointment (United Kingdom)|royal warrant]]s, one from [[Queen Elizabeth II]] (since 1962) and one from the [[Prince Charles|Prince of Wales]] (since 1990).<ref>{{cite web |title=PARKER CELEBRATES THE BRITISH MONARCH |url=https://www.parkerpen.com/en-GB/parker-celebrates-Queen-Elizabeths-90th-year |website=parkerpen.com |accessdate=12 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nParker Pen Co. was an aviation  pioneer. The interest of Parker Pen Co. about aircraft came from Kenneth Parker, son of the founder, he enlisted in the fledgling air service and, after flight training at Miami Air Base, Kenneth was assigned to officer training in tactical maneuvers at Pensacola Naval Air Station, Florida. From their first company business plane, the Parker Duofold Fairchild, they used it as an innovative advertising weapon inviting his dealers.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Campos |first1=Ramon |title=Parker: An invitation to fly. | url=https://estilograficas.mforos.com/1176620/13017601-parker-una-invitacion-a-volar-el-libro/}}</ref>\n\n==US Presidential Parkers==\nParker Jotters were a favorite choice of President [[John F. Kennedy]] for signing legislation and to give as gifts.<ref>{{cite web|title=John F. Kennedy Parker Jotter Pen|url=http://store.jfklibrary.org/john-f-kennedy-parker-jotter-pen/paaaiacnmfeikfdc/product|website=John F. Kennedy Presidential Library and Museum|publisher=JFK Library and museum|accessdate=3 February 2017|quote=President Kennedy's Favorite Pen|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905183343/http://store.jfklibrary.org/john-f-kennedy-parker-jotter-pen/paaaiacnmfeikfdc/product|archivedate=5 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Indeed, successive presidents from Kennedy to Clinton used Parker pens for these purposes, and Parker retained a special representative, John W. Gibbs, to handle White House orders. In one of his early years in office, [[Lyndon Johnson]] ordered no less than 60,000 Parker pens. LBJ would use up to 75 pens to sign each important document and bill, writing different strokes of the letters of his name with different pens, and giving them all away to allies and supporters with little typed certificates. After Parker ceased to be an American-owned company, later presidents switched to using [[A. T. Cross Company]] pens.<ref name=\"Loring\">{{cite web|last1=Loring|first1=John|title=The Presidential Pen - the first fifty years|url=http://www.loringpage.com/attpensetc/penbookupdate.html|publisher=John Loring|accessdate=3 February 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161227012404/http://www.loringpage.com/attpensetc/penbookupdate.html|archivedate=27 December 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bill Clinton Parker Insignia Set.jpg|thumb|Bill Clinton Parker Insignia Set]]\n\n==Famous models==\n[[File:Sonnet parker 3n06.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Sonnet, made from 1993]]\n\nKey models in the company's history include:\n<div style=\"-moz-column-count:3; column-count:3;\">\n* [[Parker Jointless|Jointless]] (1899), \n* Jack Knife Safety (1909), \n* [[Duofold (pen)|Duofold]] (1921), \n* [[Parker Vacumatic|Vacumatic]] (1932), \n* [[Parker 51|\"51\"]] (1941), \n* The [[Jotter]] (1954), \n* 61 (1956), \n* 45 (1964),\n* 75 (1964), \n* Classic (1967), \n* 25 (1975), \n* Arrow (1982), \n* Vector (1986), \n* Duofold International (1987),\n* 95 (1988), \n* Sonnet (1993), and \n* Parker 100 (2004)\n</div>\n{{clear}}\n\n[[Image:Parker-Vector-Plastic.jpg|thumb|eft|150px|Parker Vector plastic type]]\n[[Image:Parker-Vector-Steel.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Parker Vector steel [[Rollerball pen|rollerball tip]] type]]\n[[File:Parker Fountain pen.jpg|thumb|150px|Vector steel [[fountain pen]] type]]\n\n\n\n=== Parker 25 === \n\n[[File:Parker 25 flighters.jpg|thumb|Parker 25 flighters]]\n\nThe Parker 25 was a pen introduced by the [[Parker Pen Company]] in 1975. Created by the renowned designer [[Kenneth Grange]] based on a detailed brief,<ref> See Malcolm Toak, ''Pen to Paper, The Story of Newhaven's Pen Factory'', New Anzac Publications, 2005</ref> it was manufactured in [[Newhaven]], England and produced in a variety of different versions until 1999.<ref>See Parker Pens website, by Swedish pen historian Tony Fischier http://parkerpens.net/parker25.html</ref> An eye-catching, contemporary-looking pen, with mainly steel components, the Parker 25 was intended to revive the company's fortunes. As ''The Guardian'' wrote, '(Grange's) classic Parker pen had the machined lustre of a bullet. In fact, its tapering barrel was inspired by an American space rocket, a form that enabled the lid to be the same diameter as the pen no matter which end it was attached to.'<ref>Justin McQuirk, 'Kenneth Grange, a very British modernist', ''The Guardian'', 19 July 2011, https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2011/jul/19/kenneth-grange-british-modernist</ref> It was affordable enough to become a staple entry-level pen for both work and leisure uses - and for secondary school students at a time when fountain pens were still obligatory in many British schools. Advertising slogans used to market Parker 25s included 'Modern as Tomorrow', 'Space Age Design, Space Age Performance', 'European Styled' and 'Contemporary, Highly Functional Design'.<ref>See examples at More Engineering website created by former Parker engineer, http://www.moreengineering.co.uk/publications-and-prices/4584108238</ref>\n\nParker 25s were issued in several variants: initially, fountain pen, ballpoint, fibre point and mechanical pencil.<ref>http://www.moreengineering.co.uk/models/458277434</ref> A rollerball model was introduced in 1981, and fibre tips were phased out a couple of years later. While the great majority of Parker 25s were 'flighters', with a brushed steel finish, matte black and later white versions were issued between 1978 and 1987. The pens had four different trim colours - blue (the most common), black, green, and most rarely of all, orange. Orange trim Parker 25s were discontinued in 1976 following a copyright dispute with [[Rotring]], and surviving examples are very sought after. A striking feature of all Parker 25s is the square plastic tassie logo on the clip.\n\nThe earliest Mark I Parker 25 fountain pens dating from the first year of production feature a distinctive breather hole in the nib. While the original models had a flat plastic circle on top of the cap, Mark III and IV pens have a round ridge on this inner cap. Pens manufactured from 1980 feature letter date codes which were changed every quarter. Those manufactured from 1990 are stamped 'Made in UK'; earlier pens were inscribed 'Made in England'. Pens without any manufacture stamps, or inscribed 'Made in Aus', are very rare. Parker 25s were all assembled in Britain by hand<ref>http://www.moreengineering.co.uk/introduction/4582901246</ref> - unlike Jotters, Vectors and other mass market pens - and were very minimalist, comprising between 9 and 11 components.\n\nThe 25 was an extremely successful pen for Parker commercially, especially during its first decade or so of production.<ref>https://parkerpens.net/parker25.html</ref> A number of promotional versions were made up to order, featuring company logos on the barrel (the matte black and white versions were often branded in this way), clip or cap.\n\nSome pen aficionados are rather disparaging about the Parker 25, which lacks the status of the legendary [[Parker Duofold]]<ref>See David Shepherd and Dan Zazove, ''Parker Duofold'', Surrenden Pens Ltd, 2006.</ref> or the storied [[Parker 51]]. <ref>See David Shepherd and Mark Shepherd, ''Parker \"51\"'', Surrenden Pens Ltd, 2004.</ref> But in recent years they have been enjoying a revival, their space age look evoking nostalgia for the final quarter of the twentieth century. The Parker 25 was even given the accolade of an exhibition stand at the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]].<ref>Kenneth Grange at the Boilerhouse, Parker 25, ''Design Council Slide Collection'', Victoria and Albert Museum, https://vads.ac.uk/large.php?uid=53760&sos=0</ref>.\n\n\n===Parker Vector===\nThe precursor to the Parker Vector was introduced in 1981.  It was a simple cylindrical plastic cap and barrel [[roller-ball pen]] called the \"Parker RB1\".<ref>Note: The RB1 name stands for \"Rollerball 1\".</ref>  In 1984, Parker added the FP1 (\"Fountain Pen 1\"), with essentially the same design.  The RB1 and FP1 models were produced until 1986, at which time Parker revised the pen by lengthening the cap and shortening the barrel and renaming the new pen the \"Vector Standard\".  Presently, there are four models available (in plastic and steel): the fountain pen, capped rollerball, pushbutton ballpoint, and pushbutton pencil.<ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703493504576007640835661876 ''When Parker Pens Ruled''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170812073307/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703493504576007640835661876 |date=12 August 2017 }}; Tuesday, December 7, 2010; article; [[The Wall Street Journal]]; comment: about the relaunch of Parker Pens held at the Museum of Arts and Design on Columbus Circle.  Pictured are two Parker Vectors with polished steel finish; retrieved ???.</ref>\n\n==Products==\n*'''Products offered by the Parker Pen Company {{Asof|2012|lc=y}}:'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parkerpen.com/#/en/press|title=Welcome to Parker|website=www.parkerpen.com|accessdate=26 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315102238/http://www.parkerpen.com/#/en/press|archivedate=15 March 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left\"\n! Type !! Model\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[Parker 5TH|5TH Technology]] || I.M., Ingenuity, Sonnet, Urban\n|-\n|align=center| [[Fountain pen]]s || [[Parker Duofold|Duofold]], Premier, Frontier, Sonnet, Facet, Esprit, Urban, I.M., Vector, [[Parker Jotter|Jotter]]\n|-\n|align=center| [[Ballpoint pen]]s || Reflex, Facet, Executive, Esprit, Frontier, Urban, I.M., Vector, Jotter\n|-\n|align=center| [[Ink]]s and refills || [[Quink]], 5TH Mode\n|}\n</center>\n\n==See also==\n=== Parker brands and models ===\n* [[Parker Jointless|Jointless]]\n* [[Parker Duofold|Duofold]]\n* [[Parker 100|100]]\n* [[Parker 51|51]]\n* [[Jotter]]\n* [[Parker Vacumatic|Vacumatic]]\n* [[Parker Vector|Vector]]\n* [[Quink]]\n* [[List of pen types, brands and companies]]\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{Reflist|25em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Parker|Parker Pens}}\n* [http://www.parkerpen.com Official site]\n* [http://www.parkercollector.com Information site for 130 years of Parker pens]\n* [http://www.penhero.com/PenGallery/Parker/Parker.htm Parker pens gallery on Penhero site]\n \n{{Pen manufacturers}}\n{{Fountain pen manufacturers}}\n{{Manpower Inc.}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:British Royal Warrant holders]]\n[[Category:Fountain pen and ink manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies established in 1888]]\n[[Category:Newell Brands]]\n[[Category:Parker pens| ]]\n[[Category:Pen manufacturers]]\n[[Category:1993 mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:2000 mergers and acquisitions]]\n", "name_user": "Betongmandarin", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parker_Pen_Company"}
{"title_page": "OneAmerica 500 Festival Mini-Marathon", "text_new": "{{Infobox athletics race|bgcolour=#0053a0|image=OneAmerica_500_Festival_Mini-Marathon.png|caption=OneAmerica 500 Festival Mini-Marathon logo|date=The first Saturday of May <br />Next: May 8, 2021|location=[[Indianapolis]], [[Indiana]]|type=Road|distance=[[Half marathon]]|est={{start date and age|1977|05|27}}|record=Men: 1:01:52 (2014)<br />  [[Nelson Oyugi]]<br /> Women: 1:10:59 (2010)<br />  [[Janet Cherobon]]|homepage={{Official URL}}}}[[File:Indianapolis mini-marathon at the Motor Speedway, 2018.jpg|alt=A row of runners|thumb|Mini-marathon runners reaching the [[Indianapolis Motor Speedway]] in 2018.]]\nThe '''OneAmerica 500 Festival Mini-Marathon''', which takes place in [[Indianapolis, Indiana]], is the largest [[half marathon]] in the [[United States]], and the seventh-largest running event in America.<ref>{{cite web|title=Largest Races|url=http://www.runningusa.org/statistics/largest#top100|publisher=Running USA|accessdate=6 May 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120504022720/http://www.runningusa.org/statistics/largest#top100|archivedate=4 May 2012}}</ref>  As of the 37th running in 2013, it had sold out the entire running field of 35,000 for twelve consecutive years.<ref name=\"2013 OneAmerica 500\">{{cite news | url =http://www.500festival.com/news/oneamerica-500-festival-mini-marathon-sells-out-12th-consecutive-year | title =OneAmerica 500 Festival Mini-Marathon Sells Out for 12th Consecutive Year | publisher =500Festival.com | date =2013-04-01 | accessdate =2013-07-17 | url-status =dead | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20140315052007/http://www.500festival.com/news/oneamerica-500-festival-mini-marathon-sells-out-12th-consecutive-year | archivedate =2014-03-15 }}</ref>\n\nCommonly known as \"The Mini,\" it attracts runners and spectators from all over the United States and the entire world. In 2011, participants came from all fifty states and nine countries. The race includes a men's and women's running division, as well as men's and women's wheelchair entries. The '''Delta Dental 500 Festival 5K''', a shorter version of the Mini utilizing the same start and finish lines, runs the same day.\n\nThe Mini-Marathon began in 1977 and became an official '''500 Festival''' event in 1979. The 500 Festival, a not-for-profit volunteer organization, was created in 1957 to organize civic events celebrating the [[Indianapolis 500|Indianapolis 500-Mile Race]]. Over the past 55 years, the 500 Festival has grown to become one of the largest festivals in the nation. The Mini-Marathon is one of the first events of the month of May at [[Indianapolis Motor Speedway|Indy]].\n\nThe {{convert|13.1|mi|km|adj=on}} course currently starts in [[downtown Indianapolis]], includes city streets then heads west toward [[Speedway, Indiana|Speedway]]. It includes a full loop around the [[Indianapolis Motor Speedway]], then returns to finish in the downtown area. From 1977\u20131992, the race was held the Friday before the Indianapolis 500 (part of [[Memorial Day]] weekend). Starting in 1993, the race was moved to early May, the Saturday three weeks before the race except a few exceptions.\n\nThe men's record for the Mini is 1:01:52 set by [[Nelson Oyugi]] in 2014. The women's record was set in 2010 by [[Janet Cherobon]] with a time of 1:10:59.\n\nFrom 1994\u20132004 it was known as the Indianapolis Life 500 Festival Mini-Marathon.\n\nIn 2020, the race was cancelled for the first time in its history, due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indystar.com/story/sports/2020/03/18/indianapolis-mini-marathon-canceled-first-time-43-years-coronavirus/2863524001/|title=Mini Marathon canceled for first time in 43 years|last=Woods|first=David|website=Indianapolis Star|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n==Selected history==\n===2008===\nThe race resulted in the closest finish ever in the history of the event: a tie.<ref>{{cite news| url =http://www.indystar.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080503/LOCAL18/805030481 | archive-url =https://archive.is/20130616063031/http://www.indystar.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080503/LOCAL18/805030481 | url-status =dead | archive-date =2013-06-16 | title =2008 OneAmerica 500 Festival Mini-Marathon sells out with 35,000 entries | publisher =Microchips record closest finish ever in Mini | date = 2008-05-03| accessdate = 2008-05-03}}</ref> Two Kenyan runners, Lamech Mokono and Valentine Orare, were declared co-winners, extending the streak of Kenyan victories to 13. In the women's race, defending champ Janet Cherobon made it two wins in a row. Tony Iniguez became a three-time champ in the wheelchair division.\n\n===2011===\nThe 2011 OneAmerica 500 Festival Mini-Marathon took place Saturday May 7, 2011.  A pair of newcomers brought home the men's and women's titles in the 2011 OneAmerica 500 Festival Mini-Marathon in Indianapolis. Moroccan [[Ridouane Harroufi]] took the men's race, winning in 1:02.45, while Everlyne Lagat of Kenya captured the women's race with a time of 1:11:29, snapping the four-year win streak of fellow Kenyan [[Janet Cherobon-Bawcom]], who took second. [[Adam Bleakney]] of Champaign, Ill., took advantage of the ideal conditions to win the wheelchair race with a blistering time of 49.18. The 2006 winner of the same race, Bleakney, a member of the 2008 U.S. Paralympics teams, was competing in Indianapolis for the first time since his previous win.\n\n==Past winners==\n{{legend2|#A9F5A9|'''New course record'''|border=solid 1px #AAAAAA}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Date\n!Men's winner\n!Time \n!Women's winner\n!Time\n|-\n| May 27, 1977\n| align=left|{{flagathlete|[[Frank Shorter]]|USA}} ||bgcolor=#A9F5A9|'''{{sort|1:03:56|1:03:56}}'''\n| Mary Clifford || bgcolor=#A9F5A9|'''{{sort||1:31:22|1:31:22}}'''\n|-\n| May 26, 1978\n| align=left|{{flagathlete|[[Bill Rodgers (athlete)|Bill Rodgers]]|U