=\"JHU\"/>\n|-\n|{{flagc|Greenland}}\n|11\n|0\n|11\n|[[2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Greenland]]\n|<ref name=\"JHU\"/>\n|-\n|{{flagc|Belize}}\n|10\n|2\n|8\n|[[2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Belize]]\n|<ref name=\"JHU\"/>\n|-\n|{{flagc|Montserrat}}\n|9\n|0\n|0\n|[[2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Montserrat]]\n|<ref name=\"JHU\"/>\n|-\n|{{flagc|Turks and Caicos Islands}}\n|8\n|1\n|0\n|[[2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in the Turks and Caicos Islands]]\n|<ref name=\"JHU\"/>\n|-\n|{{flagc|Nicaragua}}\n|7\n|1\n|2\n|[[2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Nicaragua]]\n|<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://nuevaya.com.ni/segunda-paciente-recuperada-de-wuhanvirus-es-dada-de-alta-en-nicaragua/ |title=\nSecond patient recovered from wuhanvirus is discharged from Nicaragua|date=5 April 2020 |publisher= Tu Nueva Radio Ya |url-status=live |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"JHU\"/>\n|-\n|{{flagc|Saint Barth\u00e9lemy}}\n|6\n|0\n|1\n|[[2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Saint Barth\u00e9lemy]]\n|<ref name=\"JHU\"/>\n|-\n|{{flagc|Anguilla}}\n|3\n|0\n|0\n|[[2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Anguilla]]\n|<ref name=\"JHU\"/>\n|-\n|{{flagc|British Virgin Islands}}\n|3\n|0\n|0\n|[[2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in the British Virgin Islands]]\n|<ref name=\"JHU\" />\n|-\n|{{flagc|Sint Eustatius}}\n|2\n|0\n|0\n|[[2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Sint Eustatius]]\n|<ref name=\"JHU\"/>\n|-\n|{{flagc|Saba}}\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|[[2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Saba]]\n|<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sabagovernment.com/news_latest.html/|title=Latest News|website=The Official Website of The Island Government of Saba|date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagc|Saint Pierre and Miquelon}}\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|[[2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Saint Pierre and Miquelon]]\n|<ref name=\"JHU\"/>\n|-\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n|'''Total'''\n|'''537,657'''\n|'''19,832'''\n|'''35,912'''\n|\n|<ref name=\"JHU\"/>\n|}\n\n== Confirmed cases ==\nCounting of cases are subject to the number of tested people.\n\n===Antigua and Barbuda===\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Antigua and Barbuda}}\n\n===The Bahamas===\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in the Bahamas}}\n\n===Barbados===\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Barbados}}\nAs of 18 March there have been two confirmed cases in the country.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://barbadostoday.bb/2020/03/17/barbados-records-first-two-cases-of-covid-19-2/ |title=Barbados records first two cases of COVID-19|date=17 March 2020 |publisher= Barbados Today |url-status=live |access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Belize===\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Belize}}\n\n=== British Overseas Territories ===\n====Anguilla====\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Anguilla}}\nThe first two cases of the virus were confirmed on 26 March.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/breaking-news-anguilla-reports-first-two-cases-of-wuhanvirus/ |title=Anguilla reports first two cases of wuhanvirus |publisher=St Lucia News Online|date=26 March 2020|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Bermuda====\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Bermuda}}\n\n====Cayman Islands====\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in the Cayman Islands}}\n\n====Montserrat====\n{{main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Montserrat}}\nThe territory's first case was confirmed on 17 March. Schools have been closed and public gatherings banned as a precautionary measure.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.loopslu.com/content/montserrat-confirms-first-case-covid-19-5 |title=Montserrat confirms first case of COVID-19\n |publisher=Loop SL|date=17 March 2020|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nationnews.com/nationnews/news/244458/montserrat-records-virus-infection |title=Montserrat records first virus infection |publisher=Nation News|date=18 March 2020|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Turks and Caicos Islands====\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in the Turks and Caicos Islands}}\n\n==== British Virgin Islands ====\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in the British Virgin Islands}}\nOn 25 March, the first two cases in the country were confirmed.<ref>{{Cite web|title=St Kitts and Nevis confirms two COVID-19 cases|url=https://bvinews.com/bvi-confirms-first-two-cases-of-wuhanvirus/|website=[[BVI News]]|accessdate=2020-03-26|language=en|publisher=|date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n===Canada===\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Canada}}\nThe first case of the [[2019\u201320 wuhanvirus pandemic|2019\u201320 wuhanvirus]] in [[Canada]] was confirmed on January 25, 2020, when a man returned to Toronto from travelling in [[Wuhan]], China and two days later, tested positive for [[wuhanvirus disease 2019]], caused by [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome wuhanvirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]. {{As of|2020|03|13|df=US}}, there have been 198 cases of wuhanvirus reported in Canada with 1 death in 7 provinces. 2 cases have been reported of the passengers who travelled on the cruise ship {{ship||Grand Princess}}: [[Ontario]] (79 cases), [[British Columbia]] (64 cases, 1 death), [[Alberta]] (29 cases), [[Quebec]] (20 cases), [[Manitoba]] (4 cases), [[Saskatchewan]] (2 cases), [[New Brunswick]] (1 case) and ''Grand Princess'' (2 cases).<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://winnipeg.ctvnews.ca/first-presumptive-case-of-covid-19-confirmed-in-manitoba-1.4849970|title=First presumptive case of COVID-19 confirmed in Manitoba|last=Rosen|first=Kayla|date=2020-03-12|website=CTV News Winnipeg|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref><ref name=\"canada100\">{{cite web |title=Canada has reported more than 100 cases of novel wuhanvirus disease |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6660614/canada-100-wuhanvirus-cases/ |website=Global News |accessdate=12 March 2020 |language=en-CA |date=11 March 2020 |quote=This brings the total to 110 as of March 11}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6666466/wuhanvirus-saskatchewan-covid-19-wuhanvirus-saskatoon/|title=Saskatchewan confirms first presumptive case of novel wuhanvirus|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref> Almost all cases had recent travel history to a country with a substantial number of wuhanvirus cases. Of these cases, eleven (six in BC, five in Ontario) have recovered.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/news-pmn/canada-news-pmn/the-latest-numbers-of-covid-19-cases-in-canada-as-of-march-13-2020|title=The latest numbers of COVID-19 cases in Canada as of March 13, 2020 &#124; National Post|first=P. M. N.|last=Canada|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of March 11, 2020, the [[Public Health Agency of Canada]] has evaluated the public health risk of the pandemic as being \"low for the general population\", but of a higher risk for those over the age of 65, or with underlying conditions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/services/diseases/2019-novel-wuhanvirus-infection.html|title=wuhanvirus disease (COVID-19): Outbreak update|last=|first=|date=2020-03-11|website=Public Health Agency of Canada|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref> On March 13, 2020 the Government of Canada issued a formal [[travel advisory]] against any non-essential travel outside of the country until further notice.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Carbert |first1=Michelle |last2=Dickson |first2=Janice |last3=Fife |first3=Robert |last4=Kirkup |first4=Kristy |title=Government asks Canadians to avoid all non-essential international travel |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-avoid-non-essential-travel-outside-canada-trudeau-urges/ |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=The Globe and Mail |date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Pandemic COVID-19 all countries: avoid non-essential travel outside Canada |url=https://travel.gc.ca/travelling/health-safety/travel-health-notices/221 |website=Travel health notices |publisher=Public Health Agency of Canada |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Costa Rica ===\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Costa Rica}}\nOn 6 March, the first case in [[Costa Rica]] was confirmed, which was also the first such case in [[Central America]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-health-wuhanvirus-costa-rica-idUKKBN20T2VT |title=Costa Rica confirms first wuhanvirus case in Central America |date=6 March 2020 |work=Reuters |access-date=6 March 2020 |via=uk.reuters.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308011226/https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-health-wuhanvirus-costa-rica-idUKKBN20T2VT |archive-date=8 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Cuba ===\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Cuba}}\nOn 11 March, the first cases in [[Cuba]] were confirmed.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-wuhanvirus-cuba/update-1-cuba-confirms-first-wuhanvirus-cases-urges-citizens-to-make-own-masks-idUSL1N2B501N?fbclid=IwAR2w3qLR013q0Thzx4R5_95FeqR6dZi86KpYL2SuQBhGyl8_qHyRlGBgSOg |title=Cuba confirms first wuhanvirus cases, urges citizens to make own masks |date=11 March 2020 |work=Reuters |access-date=11 March 2020 |via=reuters.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Greenland (Denmark)===\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Greenland}}\n{{further|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Denmark}}\n\n=== Dominica ===\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Dominica}}\nOn 22 March, the first case of COVID-19 was confirmed on the island of Dominica. It was a woman who recently came back from the UK.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.loopjamaica.com/content/watch-dominica-records-first-case-wuhanvirus-3|title=WATCH: Dominica records first case of wuhanvirus|website=www.loopjamaica.com|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Dominican Republic ===\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in the Dominican Republic}}\nOn 1 March, the first case in the Dominican Republic was confirmed, which was also the first case in the [[Caribbean]].<ref name=\"en_20200301_primercasorepublicadominicana\">{{Cite web |url=https://elnacional.com.do/republica-dominicana-confirma-el-primer-caso-de-wuhanvirus/ |title=Dominican Republic confirms the first case of wuhanvirus | work=[[El Nacional (Santo Domingo)|El Nacional]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301163521/https://elnacional.com.do/republica-dominicana-confirma-el-primer-caso-de-wuhanvirus/ |archive-date=1 March 2020 |access-date=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Dutch Caribbean ===\n==== Aruba ====\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Aruba}}\nOn 13 March 2020, [[Prime Minister of Aruba|Prime Minister]] [[Evelyn Wever-Croes]] announced the first two confirmed cases of wuhanvirus on the island.<ref name=\"FirstCases\">{{Cite news |url=https://24ora.com/dos-caso-di-wuhanvirus-na-aruba-di-cual-un-ta-arubiano/?utm_source=dlvr.it&utm_medium=twitter |title=DOS CASO DI wuhanvirus NA ARUBA DI CUAL UN TA ARUBIANO |date=13 March 2020 |work=24ora.com |language=Papiamento|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs a result, the country restricted entry of all individuals coming from Europe via air and seaports \u2013 starting on 15 March and in effect until 31 March \u2013 with the exception of those who are Aruban citizens.<ref name=\"FirstCases\"/> They also suspended public and private school classes for the week of March 16, as well as all large-scale public gatherings.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n====Cura\u00e7ao====\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Cura\u00e7ao}}\n\n====Saba====\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Saba}}\nOn 12 April, the first case was confirmed in Saba. Schools, bars and 'non essential services' are all currently shut.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Saba closes non-essential businesses due to novel wuhanvirus|url=http://www.loopnewsbarbados.com/content/saba-closes-non-essential-businesses-due-wuhanvirus-4|accessdate=2020-03-27|language=en|publisher=Loop|date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n====Sint Eustatius====\n{{main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Sint Eustatius}}\nThe two first cases on St Eustatius were confirmed on April 1.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hartvannederland.nl/nieuws/2020/liveblog-wuhanvirus-in-nederland-woensdag-1-april/|title=LIVEBLOG RIVM: 134 mensen overleden aan wuhanvirus, 1.019 nieuwe besmetttingen |website=hartvannederland.nl |access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref> Previous tests in late March had come back negative.<ref name=\"loop20200326\">{{Cite web|title=St Eustatius government tightens COVID-19 quarantine enforcement|url=http://www.loopnewsbarbados.com/content/st-eustatius-govt-tightens-covid-19-quarantine-enforcement-3|accessdate=2020-03-26|language=en|publisher=Loop|date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Schools have been temporarily shut on the island.<ref name=\"loop20200326\"/> Most international visitors are also currently banned from entering the territory.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Sint Eustatius implements travel restrictions due to COVID-19|url=http://www.loopnewsbarbados.com/content/sint-eustatius-implements-travel-restrictions-due-covid-19-4|accessdate=2020-03-27|language=en|publisher=Loop|date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\n====Sint Maarten====\n{{main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Sint Maarten}}\nAs of 18 March there has been one confirmed case in Sint Maarten.<ref name=\"slnews20200317\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/dutch-st-maarten-reports-first-case-of-covid-19/ |title=Dutch St Maarten reports first case of COVID-19 |date=17 March 2020 |publisher = St Lucia News Online|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> Schools have been shut for a period of two weeks.<ref name=\"slnews20200317\"/>\n=== El Salvador ===\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in El Salvador}}\n\n===Overseas France===\n{{further|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in France}}\nTwo cases of the wuhanvirus were confirmed on 1 March in the French [[collectivity of Saint Martin]], having travelled from France through Dutch [[Sint Maarten]] and French [[collectivity of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy]], where they infected their son who is a resident. They then returned to Sint Maarten and were detected at the airport and transferred to French Saint Martin hospital for isolation.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.smn-news.com/st-maarten-st-martin-news/34052-state-of-affairs-on-st-maarten-regarding-the-covid-19.html |title=St. Martin News Network \u2013 State of Affairs on St. Maarten regarding the COVID-19. |website=smn-news.com}}</ref>\nAccording to the [[French Ministry of Health]] situation reports,<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.santepubliquefrance.fr/maladies-et-traumatismes/maladies-et-infections-respiratoires/infection-a-wuhanvirus/articles/infection-au-nouveau-wuhanvirus-sars-cov-2-covid-19-france-et-monde |title=Infection au nouveau wuhanvirus (SARS-CoV-2), COVID-19, France et Monde |date=6 March 2020 |website=santepubliquefrance.fr |language=fr |url-status=live |access-date=6 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306003603/https://www.santepubliquefrance.fr/maladies-et-traumatismes/maladies-et-infections-respiratoires/infection-a-wuhanvirus/articles/infection-au-nouveau-wuhanvirus-sars-cov-2-covid-19-france-et-monde |archive-date=6 March 2020 }}</ref> as of 6 March, there have been two confirmed cases in [[Martinique]], two in Saint Martin and one in Saint Barth\u00e9lemy.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.santepubliquefrance.fr/content/download/234974/2524085 |title=COVID-19 : Point \u00e9pid\u00e9miologique \u2013 Situation au 6 mars 2020 |date=6 March 2020 |website=santepubliquefrance.fr |language=fr |url-status=live |access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref> As of 5 April, [[St. Pierre and Miquelon]] recorded its first verified case.<ref>{{cite web |title=SAINT-PIERRE ET MIQUELON : UN \u00abPORTEUR SAIN\u00bb, PREMIER CAS AV\u00c9R\u00c9 DE COVID-19 |url=https://www.cnews.fr/france/2020-04-05/saint-pierre-et-miquelon-un-porteur-sain-premier-cas-avere-de-covid-19-943751}}</ref>\n\n====Region of Guadeloupe====\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Guadeloupe}}\n\n====Region of Martinique====\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Martinique}}\n\n====Collectivity of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy====\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Saint Barth\u00e9lemy}}\n\n====Collectivity of Saint Martin====\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in the Collectivity of Saint Martin}}\n\n===Grenada===\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Grenada}}\nOn 22 March, the first case in the country was confirmed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.loopnewsbarbados.com/content/grenada-records-first-covid-19-case-4|title=Grenada records first COVID-19 case|website=www.loopnewsbarbados.com|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Guatemala ===\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Guatemala}}\n\n=== Haiti ===\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Haiti}}\nOn 19 March, the first two cases in the country were confirmed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-wuhanvirus-haiti-idUSKBN21700V|title=Haiti declares emergency over wuhanvirus, imposes curfew, shuts borders|newspaper=Reuters|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=26 March 2020|via=www.reuters.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Honduras ===\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Honduras}}\nOn 10 March, the first two cases in [[Honduras]] were confirmed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://covid19honduras.org/?q=primeros-casos-confirmados |title=Salud confirma los dos primeros casos de COVID-19 en el territorio hondure\u00f1o |date=11 March 2020 |via=Covid19Honduras}}</ref>\n\n=== Jamaica ===\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Jamaica}}\nThe government announced a travel ban between China and Jamaica. All people entering Jamaica from China will be subject to immediate quarantine for at least 14 days, and anyone who was allowed to land and shows symptoms of the virus will be put in immediate isolation.<ref name=\"Jamaica Imposes Travel Ban Over wuhanvirus\">{{Cite web |url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/article/news/20200131/jamaica-imposes-travel-ban-over-wuhanvirus |title=Jamaica imposes travel ban over wuhanvirus |date=31 January 2020 |website=jamaica-gleaner.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202190241/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/article/news/20200131/jamaica-imposes-travel-ban-over-wuhanvirus |archive-date=2 February 2020 |access-date=8 February 2020}}</ref> In keeping with the new policy, 19 Chinese nationals who arrived at the [[Norman Manley International Airport]] on the evening of 31 January were denied entry, quarantined and put on a flight back to China on 1 February.<ref name=\"Jamaica turns back 19 Chinese nationals under wuhanvirus travel ban\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.loopjamaica.com/content/jamaica-turns-back-19-chinese-nationals-under-wuhanvirus-travel-ban |title=Jamaica turns back 19 Chinese nationals under wuhanvirus travel ban |website=loopjamaica.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208050344/http://www.loopjamaica.com/content/jamaica-turns-back-19-chinese-nationals-under-wuhanvirus-travel-ban |archive-date=8 February 2020 |access-date=8 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 March, the Ministry of Health and Wellness (MoHW) confirmed the first case in Jamaica, a female patient who arrived from the United Kingdom on 4 March. The health minister reported that she has been in isolation since 9 March after showing respiratory symptoms. Following the update, the travel ban imposed was expanded to include France, Germany and Spain.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/article/news/20200310/update-jamaica-confirms-first-case-wuhanvirus-travel-ban-expanded |title=Update: Jamaica confirms first case of wuhanvirus, travel ban expanded |date=10 March 2020 |website=jamaica-gleaner.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 March, the country's health minister confirmed the second \"imported corona virus {{sic}}\" case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/IRIE_FM/status/1237857780523888643|title=BREAKING NEWS: Health Minister Dr Christopher Tufton this afternoon confirmed the second case of COVID-19 via Twitter.pic.twitter.com/hLtG7ya38y|date=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Mexico ===\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Mexico}}\nOn 28 February 2020, [[Mexico]] confirmed its first three cases.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2020/02/28/mexico-confirms-its-first-2-wuhanvirus-cases/ |title=Mexico Confirms Its First 2 wuhanvirus Cases |date=28 February 2020 |website=CBS Los Angeles |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228173100/https://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2020/02/28/mexico-confirms-its-first-2-wuhanvirus-cases/ |archive-date=28 February 2020 |access-date=28 February 2020}}</ref> The country's first wuhanvirus-related death was reported on 18 March. Almost every state reported at least one case of infection.<ref>[https://www.aa.com.tr/en/americas/mexico-confirms-first-wuhanvirus-death/1771362 Mexico confirms first wuhanvirus death] by Vakkas Dogantekin, AA (Turkey), 19 March 2020, retrieved 29 March 2020</ref> Mexico entered Phase 2 of 3, indicating community transmission, on 24 March. Mexico had 292 imported cases of infection, 70 cases linked to importation, and five cases that were unlinked to foreign contact.<ref>[https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/english/covid-19-mexico-has-entered-second-phase-its-contingency-plan Covid-19 Mexico: has entered the second phase of its contingency plan] {{in lang|en}} El Universal, 24 Mar 2020, retrieved 28 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n=== Nicaragua ===\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Nicaragua}}\n\n=== Panama ===\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Panama}}\nThe Panamanian government has enhanced its sanitary control and screening measures at all ports of entry, to prevent the spread of the virus, isolating and testing potential cases.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tvn-2.com/nacionales/Panama-aumenta-alerta-sanitaria-wuhanvirus_0_5493200713.html |title=Panam\u00e1 aumenta alerta sanitaria por wuhanvirus |date=21 January 2020 |website=TVN |language=Spanish |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200122073244/https://www.tvn-2.com/nacionales/Panama-aumenta-alerta-sanitaria-wuhanvirus_0_5493200713.html |archive-date=22 January 2020 |access-date=22 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 March, the health ministry (MINSA) announced Panama's first wuhanvirus case, a Panamanian woman in her 40s who had returned from Spain.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.telemetro.com/nacionales/2020/03/10/minsa-anuncia-wuhanvirus-panama/2656443.html |title=Ministerio de Salud confirma primer caso de wuhanvirus en Panam\u00e1 |last=Gonz\u00e1lez |first=Teiga Castrell\u00f3n/Nimay |date=9 March 2020 |website=Telemetro}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tvn-2.com/nacionales/Autoridades-confirman-defuncion-wuhanvirus-Panama_0_5529197119.html |title=Autoridades confirman primer caso por wuhanvirus en Panam\u00e1 |date=9 March 2020 |website=TVN}}</ref>\n\nOn the following day, the MINSA announced seven more COVID-19 cases and one wuhanvirus-related death.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.telemetro.com/nacionales/2020/03/11/minsa-wuhanvirus-panama/2660966.html |title=Minsa confirma 8 casos de wuhanvirus en Panam\u00e1, 66 personas est\u00e1n en observaci\u00f3n |last=Gonz\u00e1lez |first=Nimay |date=10 March 2020 |website=Telemetro}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tvn-2.com/nacionales/Colegio-Monsenor-Francisco-Beckman-COVID-19_0_5529947041.html |title=Reportan un muerto y ocho casos de wuhanvirus en Panam\u00e1 |date=10 March 2020 |website=TVN}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.prensa.com/sociedad/8-casos-de-wuhanvirus-en-panama-anuncia-el-minsa/ |title=Panam\u00e1 reporta su primer fallecido por wuhanvirus; hay ocho casos en total |work=[[La Prensa (Panama City)|La Prensa Panam\u00e1]] |date=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Saint Kitts and Nevis ===\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Saint Kitts and Nevis}}\nOn 25 March, the first two cases in the country were confirmed.<ref>{{Cite web|title=St Kitts and Nevis confirms two COVID-19 cases|url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/st-kitts-and-nevis-confirms-two-covid-19-cases/|website=St. Lucia News Online|accessdate=2020-03-26|language=en|publisher=|date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n=== Saint Lucia ===\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Saint Lucia}}\n\n=== Saint Vincent and the Grenadines ===\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Saint Vincent and the Grenadines}}\nOn 11 March, [[Saint Vincent and the Grenadines]] confirmed its first case.<ref>{{Cite web|title=BREAKING NEWS: St. Vincent confirms first case of wuhanvirus disease COVID-19|url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/breaking-news-st-vincent-confirms-first-case-of-wuhanvirus-disease-covid-19/|website=St. Lucia News Online|date=2020-03-12|accessdate=2020-03-12|language=en-US|last=Admin}}</ref>\n\n=== Trinidad and Tobago ===\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Trinidad and Tobago}}\nOn 12 March, [[Trinidad and Tobago]] confirmed its first case of [[COVID-19]]. It was a 52-year-old man who had recently been to [[Switzerland]]. He was self-isolated before he began experiencing symptoms of [[COVID-19]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=T&T confirms first case of wuhanvirus|url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/tt-gets-first-case-of-wuhanvirus-covid-19/|website=St. Lucia News Online|date=2020-03-12|accessdate=2020-03-12|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== United States ===\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in the United States}}\nOn 21 January, the United States confirmed its first case, a 35-year-old man living in [[Snohomish County, Washington]], who had travelled from Wuhan to [[Seattle\u2013Tacoma International Airport]] on 15 January.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nOn 27 February, the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] reported a case in California which may be the first instance of community transmission in the US.<ref name=\"nyt20200226\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/26/world/asia/wuhanvirus-news.html |title=In U.S. and Germany, Community Transmission Is Now Suspected |date=26 February 2020 |via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 February, officials of [[2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Washington (state)|Washington State]] confirmed the first reported death from wuhanvirus in the US.<ref name=\"united.states.1\">{{Cite web |url=https://apnews.com/f175d89567a26d59cab27725c9e8a0d7 |title=Archived copy |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229185451/https://apnews.com/f175d89567a26d59cab27725c9e8a0d7 |archive-date=29 February 2020 |access-date=29 February 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn 9 March, the United States remained still limited in its capacity to test people for the illness.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2020/03/wuhanvirus-testing-numbers/607714/|title=The Dangerous Delays in U.S. wuhanvirus Testing Haven't Stopped|last=Madrigal|first=Robinson Meyer, Alexis C.|date=2020-03-09|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, the [[United States]] was reported to have more [[2019\u201320 wuhanvirus pandemic|confirmed wuhanvirus infection cases]] than any other country in the world, including [[China]].<ref name=\"SA-20200326\">{{cite news |last1=Berke |first1=Jeremy |last2=McFall-Johnsen |first2=Morgan |title=USA Now Has More COVID-19 Cases Than Any Other Country in The World |url=https://www.sciencealert.com/usa-is-now-the-centre-of-the-covid-19-outbreak-as-their-case-numbers-top-italy-s |date=26 March 2020 |work=ScienceAlert.com |accessdate=27 March 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"NYT-20200326\">{{cite news |last=McNeil, Jr. |first=Donald G. |title=The U.S. Now Leads the World in Confirmed wuhanvirus Cases - Following a series of missteps, the nation is now the epicenter of the pandemic. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/26/health/usa-wuhanvirus-cases.html |date=26 March 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=27 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\nOn 11 April, the United States surpassed Italy as the country with the most confirmed wuhanvirus deaths,<ref>https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/health/2020/04/11/wuhanvirus-us-more-covid-19-deaths-than-italy-any-country/5121962002/</ref><ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/11/us/wuhanvirus-live-updates.html</ref><ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2020/04/11/wuhanvirus-latest-news/</ref><ref>https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/04/overtake-italy-wuhanvirus-deaths-live-updates-200410232614536.html</ref> and the first to record 2,000 deaths in a single day.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Graham-Harrison|first=Emma|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/11/wuhanvirus-us-records-2000-dead-in-a-day-as-italy-and-india-extend-lockdowns|title=wuhanvirus: US records 2,000 dead in a day as Italy and India extend lockdowns|date=12 April 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=12 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Wyoming became the 50th state to be issued a disaster declaration.<ref>https://k2radio.com/president-trump-declares-disaster-in-wyoming-due-to-wuhanvirus/</ref>\n\n====Puerto Rico====\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in Puerto Rico}}\nAs of 19 March the territory has had five confirmed cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/wuhanvirus/article241295696.html|title=Puerto Rico seeks to suspend all incoming flights to battle COVID-19 spread|date=2020-03-18|website=The Miami Herald|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> On 17 March governor [[Wanda V\u00e1zquez Garced]] announced a 24/7 a lockdown, with people only allowed to leave their homes for food, gas or medicines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/03/17/puerto-rico-first-us-territory-under-24-hour-virus-isolation.html|title=Puerto Rico first US territory under 24-hour virus isolation|date=2020-03-18|website=The Jakarta Post|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\n====United States Virgin Islands====\n{{Main|2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in the United States Virgin Islands}}\nAs of 18 March two people have tested positive for the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://viconsortium.com/vi-wuhanvirus/virgin-islands-second-case-of-wuhanvirus-confirmed-in-u-s-virgin-islands|title=Second Case of wuhanvirus Confirmed in U.S. Virgin Islands|date=2020-03-16|website=The Virgin Islands Consortium|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\n== Prevention in other countries and territories ==\n\n===Caribbean Netherlands===\n====Bonaire==== \nAs of 12 April there have been no cases in the territory.<ref>{{Cite web|title=COVID-19: Regional Round Up/ 26 March 2020|url=https://dominicanewsonline.com/news/homepage/news/covid-19-regional-round-up-26-march-2020|accessdate=2020-03-26|language=en|publisher=Dominica News Online|date=2020-03-26}}</ref> The island is currently closed to international travel.<ref>{{Cite web|title=CCOVID-19: Regional Roundup/1 April, 2020; latest global numbers |url=https://dominicanewsonline.com/news/homepage/homepage-carousel/covid-19-regional-roundup-1-april-2020/|accessdate=2020-04-03|language=en|publisher=Dominica News Online|date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col}}\n*[[History of smallpox in Mexico]]\n*[[Cocoliztli epidemics]] Mexico, 1545-1548 and 1576\u20131580\n*[[Massachusetts smallpox epidemic|1633 Massachusetts smallpox epidemic]] \n*[[1775\u20131782 North American smallpox epidemic]]\n*[[1793 Philadelphia yellow fever epidemic]]\n*[[1837 Great Plains smallpox epidemic]]\n*[[1847 North American typhus epidemic]] \n*[[Spanish flu|1918 Spanish flu pandemic]]\n*[[1924 Los Angeles pneumonic plague outbreak]]\n*[[1968 flu pandemic]]\n*[[London flu|1972 London flu]]\n*[[Mumps outbreaks in the 21st century]]\n*[[2009 flu pandemic]]\n*[[2010s Haiti cholera outbreak]]\n*[[2013\u20132014 chikungunya outbreak]]\n*[[2015\u20132016 Zika virus epidemic]]\n*[[2019\u20132020 dengue fever epidemic]]\n*[[2020 wuhanvirus pandemic on cruise ships]]\n*[[2020 in the Caribbean]]\n*[[2020 in Central America]]\n*[[2020s]]\n{{End div col}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://corona.arrangy.com Worldwide wuhanvirus Map, confirmed Cases] \u2013 Map the route paths of wuhanvirus confirmed cases.\n* [https://systems.jhu.edu/research/public-health/ncov/ ncov \u2013 CSSE] - Map of the expansion of the virus in Europe and in the world\n* [https://wuhanvirus-updates.live/country/north-america wuhanvirus Updates in North America] - Daily updated totals of the virus in all countries on North America\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 wuhanvirus pandemic in North America| ]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 wuhanvirus pandemic by continent|North America]]\n[[Category:2020 disasters in North America|wuhanvirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Health disasters in North America]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in North America]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in North America}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in North America\n| map1 = \n| map2 = \n| legend2 = \n| map3 = \n| legend3 = \n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[North America]]\n| first_case = [[Snohomish County, Washington]], [[United States]]\n| arrival_date = 21 January 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=21|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}} ago)\n| origin = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| recovery_cases =   39,220<ref name=\"coronacount\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/#countries |title=Coronavirus update (live) |date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| deaths =   21,832<ref name=\"coronacount\"/>\n| confirmed_cases = 569,342<ref name=\"coronacount\"/>\n| suspected_cases = \n| territories = 42<ref name=\"coronacount\"/>\n| total_ili = \n| website = \n}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=locations}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached [[North America]] in January 2020. As of 25 March 2020, all North American countries (including [[Central America]] and the [[Caribbean]]) have reported at least one case of [[COVID-19]].\n\n==Pandemic by country/region==\n{{main|Template:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data}} \n{{more citations needed|section|date=March 2020}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Summary table of confirmed case